04977nam a22007815i 9780813587172DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135871727 a10.36019/97808135871722doi  a(DE-B1597)563300  a(OCoLC)1154014136  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN1993.5.E82bS26 2020eb 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a791.4309472231 aSamardzija, Zoran, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPost-Communist Malaise :bCinematic Responses to European Integration /cZoran Samardzija. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (212 p.) :b0 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedia Matters00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1 Eastern European New Waves and Political Modernism -- t2 What Happens after the End of History? -- t3 Slow Cinema and the Escape from Capitalist Realism -- t4 Theo Angelopoulos, Greece, and the Ends of Europe -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe collapse of communism in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe was supposed to bring about the "end of history" with capitalism and liberal democracy achieving decisive victories. Europe would now integrate and reconcile with its past. However, the aftershocks of the financial crisis of 2008-the rise in right-wing populism, austerity politics, and mass migration-have shown that the ideological divisions which haunted Europe in the twentieth century still remain. It is within this context that Post-Communist Malaise revives discourses of political modernism and revisits debates from Marxism and seventies film theory. Analyzing work of Theo Angelopoulos, Vera Chytilová, Srdjan Dragojevic, Jean-Luc Godard, Miklós Jancsó, Emir Kusturica, Dušan Makavejev, Cristi Puiu, Jan Švankmajer, Andrei Tarkovsky, and Béla Tarr, the book focuses on how select cinemas from Eastern Europe and the Balkans critique the neoliberal integration of Europe whose failures fuel the rise of nationalism and right-wing politics. By politicizing art cinema from the regions, Post-Communist Malaise asks fundamental questions about film, aesthetics, and ideology. It argues for the utopian potential of the materiality of cinematic time to imagine a new political and cultural organization for Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCommunism and motion pictureszEurope, Eastern. 0aMotion pictureszEurope, Eastern. 0aPost-communismzEurope, Eastern. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2020z9783110704655oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2020 Englishz978311070478508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020z978311069033040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/9780813587172zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813587172423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813587172.jpg  a978-3-11-069033-0  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070478-5  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-073823-0  Art and Architecture eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aE